WEBVTT

00:01.560 --> 00:03.790
Happy. That's the word.

00:03.830 --> 00:05.627
PETRA:
Happy that you
won the election?

00:05.670 --> 00:07.638
Yes. And very grateful

00:07.670 --> 00:09.638
to all those_ _
who shared my VlSlon.

00:09.670 --> 00:12.730
It's really... a shared victory.

00:12.780 --> 00:15.169
PETRA:
A Victory
that becomes less improbable

00:15.210 --> 00:17.644
when you see Alicia Florrick
in action.

00:17.680 --> 00:20.547
ALICIA:
What do I love the most
about coming to my law firm?

00:20.580 --> 00:23.640
Well, that's easy.
The camaraderie.

00:23.690 --> 00:25.681
PETRA:
If Alicia Florrick's
a legal powerhouse,

00:25.720 --> 00:29.656
it's because she commands
the respect of her colleagues.

00:29.690 --> 00:31.658
But it wasn't always so.

00:31.690 --> 00:34.329
St. Alicia came by way
of an arduous journey.

00:34.360 --> 00:36.396
PETRA:
Can we do better
than that one?

00:36.430 --> 00:38.660
Yeah, tell me when.

00:38.700 --> 00:40.292
Uh-uh.

00:42.410 --> 00:43.809
There. No, back one.

00:43.840 --> 00:45.307
Move in on
It slowly.

00:46.740 --> 00:48.537
(rewinding)

00:48.580 --> 00:53.119
St. Alicia came by way
of an arduous journey.

00:53.150 --> 00:56.517
One that took her from
stay-at-home mom to scandal

00:56.550 --> 00:58.211
to lowly associate.

00:58.250 --> 01:00.753
The scandal photo--
can we keep her in color

01:00.790 --> 01:03.327
and make everything
else black and white?

01:06.800 --> 01:08.654
Yeah, great.
Now back to the interview.

01:08.700 --> 01:11.191
(rewinding)

01:11.230 --> 01:13.289
PETRA: _
...to lowly assoaate

01:13.340 --> 01:17.663
to founding partner of one
of Chicago's largest firms.

01:17.710 --> 01:18.836
How will _
my administration differ

01:18.870 --> 01:20.474
from that of my husband's?

01:20.510 --> 01:21.807
Mm-hmm.

01:21.840 --> 01:24.274
Well, it's not...
I can't, um... I...

01:24.310 --> 01:26.471
No, cut the stumble.

01:26.520 --> 01:28.715
(high-pitched, sped-up chatter)

01:28.750 --> 01:30.741
PETRA:
...Chicago's largest firms.

01:30.790 --> 01:32.781
ALICIA:
The better question?

01:32.820 --> 01:36.278
How will my administration be
different from my predecessor?

01:36.330 --> 01:38.628
We will be
accountable to victims,

01:38.660 --> 01:39.820
worthy of the public's trust.

01:39.860 --> 01:41.794
I'm sorry, Petra.
I need to get

01:41.830 --> 01:43.695
Mrs. Florrick on the phone with
the governor just for a moment.

01:43.730 --> 01:45.618
Sure, Eli.
Anything for you.

01:45.670 --> 01:47.535
Going great, though.
Love what you're doing.

01:47.570 --> 01:48.764
Aw, thanks.

01:48.800 --> 01:50.665
There's no one
on the phone.

01:50.710 --> 01:52.803
Just turn around and pretend
you're having a conversation.

01:52.840 --> 01:54.205
It's about the hack.

01:54.240 --> 01:55.730
Are you sure
the e-mails are safe?

01:55.780 --> 01:57.179
We're hearing
that they might still come out.

01:57.210 --> 01:58.746
Hearing from whom?

01:58.780 --> 02:00.145
I heard Diane
and Cary talking.

02:00.180 --> 02:01.613
You want some
crackers?
No.

02:01.650 --> 02:03.584
The hackers want an apology
from the firm.

02:03.620 --> 02:04.848
Well, we already resolved it.

02:04.890 --> 02:06.881
I mean, we can't
publicly condone piracy.

02:06.920 --> 02:08.217
You don't have to.

02:08.260 --> 02:09.784
"We regret any
implication

02:09.830 --> 02:11.889
that the blah-blah-blah
shareware is not
legitimate." You know.

02:11.930 --> 02:13.557
I have to consult my partners.

02:13.600 --> 02:15.420
Well, the deadline's
at the end of the week,

02:15.460 --> 02:17.724
or the e-mails go wide,
so consult fast.

02:17.770 --> 02:19.761
Thank you.

02:19.800 --> 02:21.597
(clears her throat)
PETRA:
Set?

02:21.640 --> 02:22.902
Yes, yes. Sorry about that.

02:22.940 --> 02:24.737
No, no, no.
All set.

02:24.770 --> 02:26.772
EDITOR: I was thinking of using
this stuff for the sit-down.

02:26.810 --> 02:28.778
It looks way better than
the first time she sat down.

02:28.810 --> 02:29.799
I didn't...
(phone dings)

02:31.210 --> 02:33.610
I didn't
shake her hand that time.

02:33.650 --> 02:35.811
(high-pitched, sped-up chatter)

02:42.790 --> 02:45.156
(keys clicking)

02:47.860 --> 02:49.521
ALICIA:
...and we will be transparent.

02:49.570 --> 02:53.597
Accountable to victims,
worthy of the public's trust.

02:53.640 --> 02:56.837
MAN:
Where'd you get these?

02:56.870 --> 02:58.201
An anonymous source.
They're hacked?

02:58.240 --> 02:59.639
Yes. Alicia Florrick's
hacked e-mails

02:59.680 --> 03:00.908
from the past five years.

03:00.940 --> 03:02.544
You have to read them.

03:02.580 --> 03:04.400
Thought this was
a puff piece.
It was.

03:04.450 --> 03:06.543
People don't like when
you tear down their heroes.

03:06.580 --> 03:07.945
Are you kidding?

03:07.980 --> 03:09.345
That's what they live for.

03:09.390 --> 03:10.914
I need independent
corroboration.

03:10.950 --> 03:13.555
Talk to her firm, confirm
they've been hacked.

03:13.590 --> 03:14.887
Yes, we did have an attack

03:14.920 --> 03:17.525
on our e-mail services,
but we have since...

03:17.560 --> 03:19.391
Petra Moritz.

03:19.430 --> 03:22.297
But we have since
repelled that attack.

03:22.330 --> 03:23.763
No, it's had
absolutely no impact...

03:23.800 --> 03:24.619
(elevator bell dings)

03:24.670 --> 03:26.831
ANDREW: Okay,
Daddy just needs a minute,

03:26.870 --> 03:28.599
so I need you guys
to sit quietly.

03:28.640 --> 03:29.834
Come on.
Charlie, come on.

03:29.870 --> 03:32.907
Ms. Sharma, hello.
Good to see you again.

03:32.940 --> 03:34.828
You, too, Mr. Wiley.
What are you up to today?

03:34.880 --> 03:37.576
Oh, just, you know, the
usual-- making trouble.

03:37.610 --> 03:39.475
See you later.

03:39.520 --> 03:41.374
Bye.

03:41.420 --> 03:43.411
RECEPTIONIST: Yes, well, he's
in with a client right now.

03:43.450 --> 03:46.886
Sure, I'd be happy to send you
to voice mail if that's okay.

03:46.920 --> 03:48.456
Uh, that's no
problem at all.

03:48.490 --> 03:49.855
Thank you very much.

03:49.890 --> 03:51.721
That'll be
10:00 tomorrow?

03:51.760 --> 03:54.456
(speaks indistinctly)

03:54.500 --> 03:56.866
(phone rings)
Florrick, Agos & Lockhart.

03:56.900 --> 04:00.438
*

04:02.970 --> 04:04.938
Hey, uh, everything all right?

04:04.970 --> 04:08.007
Yes, I just have to meet this
Mr. Dipple at his think tank.

04:08.040 --> 04:09.849
No, I mean in there.

04:09.880 --> 04:11.973
Oh, yes. Andrew Wiley.
You know, the investigator?

04:12.010 --> 04:14.012
Yeah. What's he asking?

04:14.050 --> 04:15.574
He's working with
Internal Affairs.

04:15.620 --> 04:18.009
Looking into Detective Prima
and how he set up Cary.

04:18.050 --> 04:19.688
Brady Violation.

04:19.720 --> 04:21.654
Yeah, and how
he entrapped Cary, too.

04:21.690 --> 04:23.726
Well, they're finding
that harder to prove.

04:23.760 --> 04:25.057
Why is he talking to us?

04:25.090 --> 04:26.853
They want to find out

04:26.900 --> 04:29.391
how we discovered that
e-mail from Canada.

04:29.430 --> 04:31.022
The one that
Prima deleted.

04:31.070 --> 04:32.765
They want to prosecute
him for this.

04:32.800 --> 04:35.291
See you.

04:39.480 --> 04:41.675
KALINDA:
Hi.
Hey.

04:41.710 --> 04:43.007
Can I help you?

04:43.050 --> 04:45.848
Yeah, uh,
I need some legal advice.

04:45.880 --> 04:48.371
Okay.

04:48.420 --> 04:50.411
Hypothetically, a cop
is going to prison

04:50.450 --> 04:51.986
for something
that he didn't do.

04:52.020 --> 04:53.885
Someone else did it.

04:53.920 --> 04:55.888
But there's a lavwer
who made misrepresentations

04:55.920 --> 04:59.048
based on... on, um...

04:59.090 --> 05:00.557
I, um...

05:00.600 --> 05:02.921
Just don't use names,
and I'm fine.

05:02.970 --> 05:06.929
Look... someone is guilty

05:06.970 --> 05:09.438
of faking evidence,

05:09.470 --> 05:11.665
but a lawyer
who did not fake that evidence,

05:11.710 --> 05:13.974
and, in fact,
thought it to be true,

05:14.010 --> 05:15.477
presented it in court.

05:15.510 --> 05:17.649
Now, is that lavwer in trouble?

05:17.680 --> 05:19.341
What, for using
the faked evidence?

05:19.380 --> 05:21.678
Yeah. Even though she didn't
know that it was faked?

05:21.720 --> 05:23.119
Mm-hmm, yes.

05:23.150 --> 05:25.038
Ignorance is irrelevant.

05:25.090 --> 05:27.513
The lawyer could be disbarred
or even go to prison.

05:29.990 --> 05:32.527
Okay, and, uh,

05:32.560 --> 05:36.997
what if that person
who faked the evidence swore

05:37.030 --> 05:38.566
to the lawyer's innocence?

05:38.600 --> 05:40.989
Doesn't matter.
It's strict liability.

05:43.070 --> 05:45.402
Okay.

05:45.440 --> 05:47.032
Anything else?

05:47.080 --> 05:48.399
No.

05:48.440 --> 05:50.499
Uh, that's enough.
Thank you.

05:50.550 --> 05:52.973
Sure.

05:53.020 --> 05:54.942
(door closes)

05:58.020 --> 05:59.885
Diane,

05:59.920 --> 06:01.649
you brave soul, welcome
to the Plenary Institute.

06:01.690 --> 06:03.453
How am I brave?

06:03.490 --> 06:07.051
Liberal lavwer in this lion's
den of conservatism?
(laughs)

06:07.100 --> 06:10.467
A lion's den is perfectly safe
when you have God on your side.

06:10.500 --> 06:13.435
Ah, there she is,
quoting the Bible. Diane,

06:13.470 --> 06:16.030
may I introduce Max Gauls,
Cole-Harberts-Greyson?

06:16.070 --> 06:18.061
Nice to meet you.
Justin Partridge
of Simkins-Wilde.

06:18.110 --> 06:19.737
It's so good
to meet you.

06:19.780 --> 06:22.101
Diane, have a seat
right over here.
Okay.

06:22.140 --> 06:23.903
So, what am I doing?

06:23.950 --> 06:26.646
Aside from picking up
your retainer check?

06:26.680 --> 06:28.113
I need a liberal viewpoint.

06:28.150 --> 06:29.686
On?

06:29.720 --> 06:31.119
Gay marriage.

06:31.150 --> 06:33.084
You're the devil's advocate.

06:33.120 --> 06:35.418
In what way?
We're trying
to decide

06:35.460 --> 06:37.428
whether to fund a case
on gay marriage

06:37.460 --> 06:39.121
and religious accommodation.

06:39.160 --> 06:40.991
And what is the case?

06:41.030 --> 06:43.919
In May of 2014, Jane Armisen,
a baker in California,

06:43.970 --> 06:46.632
was asked to bake a cake
for a gay wedding.

06:46.670 --> 06:50.629
She refused,
citing religious objections

06:50.670 --> 06:53.173
to supporting gay marriage,
and was sued for discrimination.

06:53.210 --> 06:55.838
She lost.
And you're wondering whether

06:55.880 --> 06:57.074
to take up this baker's appeal?

06:57.110 --> 06:59.840
Yup.
No.

06:59.880 --> 07:02.019
Obviously.
Well, that's not surprising.

07:02.050 --> 07:04.189
(Diane laughs)

07:04.220 --> 07:05.778
Well, it's not because
I'm a liberal.

07:05.820 --> 07:07.515
It's because... you won't win.

07:07.560 --> 07:09.118
I mean, this was
a plain wedding cake?

07:09.160 --> 07:11.048
There was nothing
about the cake itself

07:11.090 --> 07:13.524
that was offensive to the baker?

07:13.560 --> 07:15.221
That's correct. It's the fact
it would have been used

07:15.260 --> 07:17.194
in a ceremony she believes
dishonored her religious creed.

07:17.230 --> 07:19.027
But this baker

07:19.070 --> 07:22.039
advertises to the public that
she makes these wedding cakes,

07:22.070 --> 07:23.105
and she will sell

07:23.140 --> 07:24.903
these wedding cakes to anyone,

07:24.940 --> 07:26.202
just not gay people.

07:26.240 --> 07:28.105
I'm sorry,

07:28.140 --> 07:30.643
but that's not
a strong case.
Well, the Constitution

07:30.680 --> 07:33.046
guarantees her the free exercise
of religion.

07:33.080 --> 07:35.469
And California's Civil Rights
Act forbids discrimination

07:35.520 --> 07:37.647
against LGBT people.

07:37.690 --> 07:39.214
REESE:
So, we have two
competing freedoms.

07:39.250 --> 07:42.253
Businesses are allowed
to refuse serwce to anyone.

07:42.290 --> 07:45.179
With certain exceptions
to that right.

07:45.230 --> 07:47.095
It cannot be based on race,

07:47.130 --> 07:50.167
color, religion
or sexual orientation.

07:50.200 --> 07:51.622
In some states,
sexual orientation.

07:51.670 --> 07:53.069
In many states.

07:53.100 --> 07:54.567
Well, but there are
exceptions to the exceptions.

07:54.600 --> 07:55.828
What did Thomas
Jefferson say?

07:55.870 --> 07:58.065
"Among the most inestimable

07:58.110 --> 08:00.271
"of our blessings is that
of liberty

08:00.310 --> 08:02.107
"to worship our Creator

08:02.140 --> 08:04.142
in a way we think
would be agreeable to Him."

08:04.180 --> 08:06.648
It's no different from
conSCIentious objectors to war.

08:06.680 --> 08:08.147
I'm sorry to be blunt.

08:08.180 --> 08:10.148
I know you come
to your opinions honestly.

08:10.190 --> 08:12.181
Well, it's not just my opinion.

08:12.220 --> 08:14.654
The Religious Freedom
Restoration Act allows

08:14.690 --> 08:17.079
exemptions in
anti-discrimination laws.
Not in California.

08:17.130 --> 08:18.984
California does not have one.
Well, let's say

08:19.030 --> 08:20.657
we're-we'renot
in California.

08:20.700 --> 08:22.668
Let's say we're
in Colorado.

08:22.700 --> 08:24.691
(bell tinkles)

08:24.730 --> 08:27.096
DIANE:
Okay, well, we're not
in Colorado, but RFRA

08:27.140 --> 08:28.835
would not be your
friend there, either.

08:28.870 --> 08:30.167
So, let's say
it's in New Mexico.

08:30.210 --> 08:31.563
DIANE:
It doesn't matter.

08:31.610 --> 08:32.907
The baker's refusing

08:32.940 --> 08:34.168
to sell a wedding cake

08:34.210 --> 08:36.201
to a gay couple
for who they are.

08:36.240 --> 08:38.902
That is the heart
of discrimination.

08:38.950 --> 08:41.612
REESE:
What if our baker won't sell
a wedding cake to a gay couple,

08:41.650 --> 08:44.187
but he will sell them
bear claws?

08:44.220 --> 08:46.279
Cupcakes?
MAX:
That's right.

08:46.320 --> 08:48.049
She isn't, in fact,
refusing to serve homosexuals.

08:48.090 --> 08:49.751
She just won't do the one thing

08:49.790 --> 08:51.257
her religion says is a sin.

08:51.290 --> 08:53.724
Okay.

08:53.760 --> 08:56.194
That's a good point.

08:56.230 --> 08:59.961
Great. Let's take
a little break.

09:00.000 --> 09:03.163
So, um, where is Diane Lockhart?

09:03.210 --> 09:04.768
I'm sorry?

09:04.810 --> 09:06.163
"That's a good point"?

09:06.210 --> 09:07.677
It was a good point.
No, it wasn't.

09:07.710 --> 09:09.769
You know it wasn't.
Well, you wanted me to help.

09:09.810 --> 09:11.209
No, I want you to fight.

09:11.250 --> 09:13.775
I want you to convince me
this is a loser case.

09:13.820 --> 09:15.879
If you're worried
about offending me, don't.

09:15.920 --> 09:17.979
I have a gay nephew, okay?

09:18.020 --> 09:20.784
Love my gay nephew,
want him to be happy.

09:20.820 --> 09:24.051
I just don't happen to believe
in gay marriage. You do.

09:24.090 --> 09:27.218
Convince me I'm wrong.
Go for the jugular?

09:27.260 --> 09:29.967
Mm-hmm, right there,
ma'am. Right there.
(laughs)

09:30.000 --> 09:33.265
That's insane. Selling someone
something they don't want is

09:33.300 --> 09:35.063
the same thing as refusing
them service altogether.

09:35.100 --> 09:36.328
No, it isn't. You
can't even compare...

09:36.370 --> 09:38.167
A vegetarian couple walks
into a market,

09:38.210 --> 09:40.178
and you refuse
to sell them vegetables.

09:40.210 --> 09:42.303
In fact, you'll sell them
anything but vegetables.

09:42.340 --> 09:44.843
You are effectively
denying them service.

09:44.880 --> 09:47.178
A gay couple wants
to buy a wedding cake,

09:47.220 --> 09:49.279
and you refuse
to sell them a wedding cake.

09:49.320 --> 09:51.185
(high-pitched, sped-up chatter)

09:51.220 --> 09:53.279
ALICIA:
The camaraderie,
the relationships

09:53.320 --> 09:56.016
I've built _here-- it's what
makes coming to work a joy.

09:56.060 --> 09:57.880
Relationships
that have been built

09:57.930 --> 10:00.296
with some difficulty...
apparently.

10:00.330 --> 10:01.991
Now cut to the e-mail.

10:02.030 --> 10:03.861
Float it in,
Star Wars style.

10:05.030 --> 10:07.089
(beeping)

10:08.970 --> 10:10.904
"It's all about money to them.

10:10.940 --> 10:13.101
The partners don't
give a damn about us."

10:13.140 --> 10:14.903
Float in the second e-mail.

10:14.940 --> 10:17.374
"The partners don't give a damn
about us."

10:17.410 --> 10:19.674
Two of her coworkers write:

10:19.720 --> 10:21.745
"Alicia is a perfect example

10:21.780 --> 10:23.782
of someone sleeping her way
to the top."

10:23.820 --> 10:25.139
Now change the music.

