reporter Ted Willoughby

37:52.900 --> 37:55.733
of Channel 8
just a few hours ago,

37:55.770 --> 37:58.409
those e-mails were part
of an unfortunate

37:58.440 --> 38:00.067
flirtation.
That's it.

38:00.110 --> 38:01.600
Well, uh, surely the-the...

38:01.640 --> 38:05.349
the-the language
in-in these e-mails

38:05.380 --> 38:08.918
is not, uh, everyday talk
between a superior and-and

38:08.950 --> 38:10.747
subordinate.
Well, that's a picture

38:10.780 --> 38:13.510
you seem intent on painting.
I guess what my chief of staff

38:13.550 --> 38:15.518
Eli Gold said to Kim Masters

38:15.560 --> 38:17.380
in their interview
is true.

38:17.420 --> 38:19.388
You're out
to get her.
No, I-I-I...

38:20.660 --> 38:22.548
I am just trying
to reveal the truth,

38:22.600 --> 38:24.397
Governor, and...
Look, Petra,

38:24.430 --> 38:27.695
you've been trying to nail
Alicia for the last three years.

38:27.730 --> 38:30.563
Governor...
You have a grudge
against her. You do.

38:30.600 --> 38:32.909
I mean, if you look at any of
your interviews with her...
Okay, thank you,

38:32.940 --> 38:34.874
thank you. I think we
have what we need here.

38:34.910 --> 38:37.799
Okay. We're good?
Yes, and thank you
for... coming down.

38:37.840 --> 38:39.649
Oh, no, thank you.

38:39.680 --> 38:41.102
I think that went well.

38:41.150 --> 38:43.038
Hey, thank you.
Good to see you.

38:43.080 --> 38:45.082
Okay,
thank you.

38:54.930 --> 38:56.591
ANDREW:
Speeding tickets?

38:56.630 --> 38:58.769
How many?
Uh, four.

38:58.800 --> 39:01.598
Uh, there were
four, but he only

39:01.640 --> 39:03.938
fixed two for me--
I paid for the other two.

39:03.970 --> 39:05.107
Just to keep it kosher?

39:05.140 --> 39:06.459
Yeah.

39:06.510 --> 39:07.738
Where'd you get 'em?

39:07.770 --> 39:09.977
Two in the Loop

39:10.010 --> 39:12.672
and one on the way
back from Springfield.

39:12.710 --> 39:14.575
The other on
the, uh, South Side.

39:14.620 --> 39:15.917
That's exactly what Howell said.

39:15.950 --> 39:17.975
Almost word for word.

39:18.020 --> 39:19.817
I got to go.

39:19.850 --> 39:21.488
There's a puppet show
at the library.

39:21.520 --> 39:23.681
One last thing, Kalinda.

39:25.890 --> 39:27.858
You're caught.

39:27.890 --> 39:29.858
You faked the metadata.

39:32.030 --> 39:33.759
The longer it takes
for you to admit it,

39:33.800 --> 39:35.438
the worse it's gonna be
for you and Diane.

39:35.470 --> 39:37.995
So, I mean, I hate to say this,

39:38.040 --> 39:40.600
'cause I like you, but...

39:40.640 --> 39:42.779
if I were you, I'd come clean.

39:42.810 --> 39:44.129
Come on.

39:45.750 --> 39:48.878
(door opens, closes)

39:48.920 --> 39:50.979
Well, you've given this old

39:51.020 --> 39:53.545
con law professor
a lot to think about.

39:54.220 --> 39:55.949
On the one hand, people

39:55.990 --> 39:57.810
have the right
to their religious views,

39:57.860 --> 39:59.487
and they cannot
and should not

39:59.530 --> 40:01.851
be barred from the marketplace
because of them.

40:01.900 --> 40:03.891
On the other hand,
every citizen has the right

40:03.930 --> 40:05.192
not to be discriminated against

40:05.230 --> 40:06.891
on the basis
of their race,

40:06.930 --> 40:08.568
their color,
their nationality,

40:08.600 --> 40:10.932
and yes,
their sexual orientation.

40:10.970 --> 40:13.131
Well, given all that,

40:13.170 --> 40:16.003
my task is difficult but clear:

40:16.040 --> 40:17.974
I must weigh whether or not

40:18.010 --> 40:19.568
a religious
accommodation

40:19.610 --> 40:21.168
would frustrate the core purpose

40:21.210 --> 40:23.178
of antidiscrimination
law.

40:23.220 --> 40:26.018
And in this case...

40:26.050 --> 40:27.039
I find that it would.

40:27.090 --> 40:29.058
Accordingly,
I must rule

40:29.090 --> 40:30.887
in favor of the plaintiffs,

40:30.920 --> 40:34.083
Mr. Taylor
and Mr. Andersen.

40:35.630 --> 40:37.848
Very well done.

40:44.940 --> 40:48.068
Diane. Can I_ ask
you something?

40:48.110 --> 40:51.034
What do you think would happen

40:51.080 --> 40:53.844
if every case were adjudicated

40:53.880 --> 40:56.144
by someone with a family member

40:56.180 --> 40:59.616
or loved one who'd be affected
by the decision?

40:59.650 --> 41:01.959
Ultimately, perhaps
every case is.

41:01.990 --> 41:04.083
But isn't the law supposed
to be impersonal?

41:04.120 --> 41:06.953
In the sense that it should
be the same for everyone?

41:06.990 --> 41:08.958
You know, otherwise
we're in China,

41:09.000 --> 41:10.991
right? Everything's
determined by who you know.

41:11.030 --> 41:12.998
The law is supposed to be fair.

41:13.030 --> 41:15.692
Not impersonal.

41:15.740 --> 41:16.934
In fact, I would argue

41:16.970 --> 41:19.837
that the law is always personal.

41:19.870 --> 41:22.031
It has to see
the human side, too.

41:22.080 --> 41:23.809
Or else it's meaningless.

41:27.010 --> 41:29.012
Hmm.

41:29.050 --> 41:31.883
You're gonna fund
this defense anyway, aren't you?

41:31.920 --> 41:33.945
The wedding planner?

41:33.990 --> 41:35.252
Yes.

41:35.290 --> 41:37.986
Why?

41:38.020 --> 41:40.955
Three years ago, Barack Obama

41:40.990 --> 41:42.890
was against gay marriage.

41:42.930 --> 41:45.569
So was Bill Clinton.
So was Hillary.

41:45.600 --> 41:48.569
You know, b-basically
every Democratic icon

41:48.600 --> 41:50.739
was lined up
against gay marriage.

41:50.770 --> 41:53.659
Now they're not.
You know?

41:53.710 --> 41:57.134
Because it's politically
expedient for them not to be.

41:57.180 --> 41:59.705
Who knows what they're
gonna be for or against

41:59.750 --> 42:01.718
in another three
years, right?

42:01.750 --> 42:06.187
I like people who stand
by their opinions.

42:06.220 --> 42:09.018
I like people
who stand by their beliefs.

42:09.060 --> 42:11.119
And I think

42:11.160 --> 42:13.128
a religious accommodation

42:13.160 --> 42:15.799
must be made
for people who do that.

42:15.830 --> 42:18.151
You know?
It's the right thing to do.

42:20.030 --> 42:21.668
PETRA:
And as we've discussed,

42:21.700 --> 42:24.567
you're a highly educated,
very confident woman,

42:24.610 --> 42:26.305
but you walk into this

42:26.340 --> 42:28.934
law firm, full of old bulls

42:28.980 --> 42:31.130
and young tigers.
Were you nervous?

42:31.180 --> 42:32.841
Oh, very.

42:32.880 --> 42:35.110
That's nice.
Very human.
Just wait.

42:35.150 --> 42:37.141
PETRA:
During our time together,

42:37.180 --> 42:38.943
Mrs. Florrick talked about
what she had learned

42:38.990 --> 42:40.844
as an attorney.
About the importance

42:40.890 --> 42:43.688
of being smart,
creative, zealous.

42:43.720 --> 42:44.948
But the question surfacing

42:44.990 --> 42:47.925
in recent days is this: was

42:47.960 --> 42:50.224
Alicia Florrick
the candidate too creative,

42:50.260 --> 42:52.865
too zealous, in her pursuit of
the state's attorney's office?

42:52.900 --> 42:55.937
What is she talking about?
I have no idea.

42:55.970 --> 42:58.268
I recently spoke
with a Chicago election monitor,

42:58.300 --> 43:01.337
and serious accusations
are being made

43:01.370 --> 43:03.679
that the voting machines
in some wards

43:03.710 --> 43:06.349
registered votes for Frank Prady

43:06.380 --> 43:08.769
as votes for Alicia Florrick.

43:08.820 --> 43:10.879
Mother of...
PETRA: And that may have
been the difference

43:10.920 --> 43:13.138
in the state's attorney race.
What?
Oh...

43:13.190 --> 43:16.216
we are all in trouble now.
PETRA: Was the election stolen?
For now we don't know...

